properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow accompanied by strong winds will give widespread blowing snow Tuesday. In addition, it should be noted that the system associated with these weather conditions could give snow in excess of 20 centimetres by Wednesday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Arctic air continues to move throughout BC. Following a relatively mild first half of winter, a transition to much colder conditions continues throughout BC. Cold Arctic air over the BC interior will continue to flow towards the BC coast. Temperatures over Interior regions will be 10 to 20 degrees below the seasonal average, while coastal areas will be 5 to 10 degrees below seasonal, making for the coldest conditions seen this season. The cold air will persist for the remainder of the week. In addition, Arctic Outflow warnings are possible for the Fraser Valley, the Sea to Sky corridor and the Central Coast beginning Wednesday night as wind chill values approach minus 20. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls will continue tonight. Snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm are possible before the snow squall shifts slightly south of Wawa Tuesday morning. Snow squalls may return to the region Tuesday night. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Extremely cold wind chill values between minus 40 and minus 55 continue. This prolonged cold snap is expected to persist into the weekend for many areas of Alberta. There will be some moderation in temperature at times, typically during daylight hours. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Additional snowfall: 5 to 15 cm Maximum wind gusts: northeasterly 80 to 100 km/h becoming northwesterly 80 to 100 km/h. Locations: southern and eastern Newfoundland. Time span: tonight into Tuesday. Remarks: Snow will continue overnight before tapering off tomorrow. The snow combined with strong northwesterly winds will cause reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Conditions will improve early Tuesday morning for areas along the south coast as the snow tapers to flurries; however, strong northwesterly winds will persist into Tuesday afternoon which may cause reduced visibility in blowing snow over some areas. Strong northwesterly winds and periods of snow will persist over more northern areas, including the St. John's Metro area, throughout the night and into the day Tuesday before tapering to onshore flurries. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
